{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1338"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.79,0.05,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1338"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34248"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13146"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43840"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of fatigue and intermittent diarrhoea, frequently containing blood and mucus. She describes faecal urgency and an occasional feeling of incomplete defaecation. When the diarrhoea occurs, she experiences diffuse colicky abdominal pain. In addition, she has noticed erythematous painful nodules on the anterior aspect of her shins in the last week. She has not been able to associate her symptoms with dietary triggers. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications, except for a short course of antibiotics for treatment of a chest infection two months ago. She is a non-smoker and does not drink alcohol. She went on a walking holiday in Nepal three months ago. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The abdominal examination is unremarkable apart from some mild diffuse tenderness. There are several tender, erythematous lesions on the anterior aspect of both shins (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Shigellosis","Inflammatory bowel disease","Intestinal amoebiasis","Giardia infection","Clostridioides difficile colitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history of fatigue, chronic diarrhoea with blood and mucus, urgency, tenesmus, and erythema nodosum is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E (IBD), most likely ulcerative colitis. The presence of extraintestinal manifestations, such as erythema nodosum, further supports this diagnosis. IBD typically presents with chronic symptoms and can involve both gastrointestinal and systemic manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShigellosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an acute bacterial infection that typically causes sudden onset of severe diarrhoea, often bloody, with abdominal cramps and tenesmus. However, it usually resolves within 5-7 days and does not typically cause chronic symptoms or extraintestinal manifestations like erythema nodosum. The two-month duration of symptoms in this case makes shigellosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntestinal amoebiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is an important differential to be considered given the patient\u0027s travel history. It is caused by the protozoan parasite \u003Cem\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/em\u003E. It can cause a chronic diarrhoea, usually watery but sometimes bloody, which may appear similar to inflammatory bowel disease. It can also cause extraintestinal manifestations including liver abscesses and cutaneous disease, although this is typically ulcerating rather than the nodular lesions pictured. Diagnosis of amoebiasis is typically made by microscopic examination of stool samples for cysts or trophozoites, or serology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiardia infection\u003C/strong\u003E could also be considered given the patient\u0027s travel history. In giardia infection, initially stools may be watery and profuse. Later, they may become greasy and foul-smelling. Typically, tenesmus and bloody diarrhea do not occur and blood, mucus and leucocytes are absent in the stool. It does not cause extraintestinal manifestations like erythema nodosum. The presence of bloody diarrhoea and skin lesions make giardiasis an unlikely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/strong\u003E colitis is an important consideration given the recent antibiotic use. Diarrhoea may occurs from several days to as long as two months after antibiotic treatment, with a wide spectrum of presentation (mild, self-limited diarrhoea, pseudomembranous colitis and fulminant colitis). It usually presents with mild to moderate watery diarrhea that is rarely bloody. In this patient, the presentation with bloody diarrhoea and erythema nodosum make inflammatory bowel disease a more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while all these conditions can cause diarrhoea, the chronic nature of the symptoms, the presence of blood and mucus in the stool, and the extraintestinal manifestation of erythema nodosum strongly support the diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease. Further investigations, including stool studies, colonoscopy, and biopsy, would be necessary to confirm the diagnosis and determine the specific type of IBD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clinical features of IBD include diarrhoea often with blood and mucus, urgency, abdominal pain, and may include extraintestinal manifestations such as erythema nodosum.","It is important to consider and rule out infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea, which may mimic IBD"],"references":["JUCKETT G, TRIVEDI R. Evaluation of Chronic Diarrhea. Am Fam Physician . 2011;84(10):1119\u201326."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34248"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1338"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17517"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17517"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/64376615-6e8e-4e55-9339-251046c5f1f7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/64376615-6e8e-4e55-9339-251046c5f1f7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":272,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34248"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-24T14:21:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-24T14:21:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}